#### Equipment

Initially skilled archers, Janissaries quickly adopted [firearms](/Firearms) in the 1440s. Their engineers were renowned, particularly at sieges like the [Siege of Vienna in 1529](/Siege_of_Vienna_(1529)). In close combat, they wielded [axes](/Axe) and [kilijs](/Kilij). In peacetime, they carried clubs or [daggers](/Dagger), unless serving on the frontiers. The Turkish [yatagan](/Yataghan) became their signature weapon. By the early 16th century, they were proficient with [muskets](/Shishane), including a formidable "trench gun." They also utilized early [grenades](/Grenades) and [hand cannons](/Hand_cannon), such as the [abus gun](/Abus_gun). [Pistols](/Pistol) gained popularity after the [Cretan War (1645–1669)](/Cretan_War_(1645%E2%80%931669)).

### Battles

The Janissaries were deployed in all major Ottoman campaigns, including the [capture of Constantinople](/Fall_of_Constantinople) in 1453, battles against the [Mamluk Sultanate of Cairo](/Mamluk_Sultanate_of_Cairo), and wars in [Hungary](/Hungary) and [Austria](/Austria). They were often led by the Sultan himself and shared in the spoils of [loot](/Looting). As the sole infantry division, their primary role was to protect the Sultan, employ firearms, and hold the center against enemy cavalry during feigned retreats. They also comprised specialized units of explosives experts, engineers, sharpshooters, and sappers.

### Revolts and Disbandment

As the Janissaries' influence grew, so did their desire for privilege. By the early 17th century, they dominated the government, capable of mutiny, dictating policy, and obstructing military modernization. They even orchestrated [palace coups](/Palace_coup) to depose Sultans. New regulations allowed them to own property and engage in business, further eroding their martial focus. Their first revolt demanding higher wages occurred in 1449, which they successfully obtained. This set a precedent for their increasing assertiveness, much like the [Streltsy](/Streltsy) in Russia or the [Praetorian Guard](/Praetorian_Guard) in Rome. Every new Sultan felt compelled to pay them a reward and increase their pay. The permission granted to Janissaries to marry in 1566 by [Selim II](/Selim_II) undermined their singular loyalty. By 1622, they posed a "serious threat" to the Empire's stability. Their "greed and indiscipline" made them a law unto themselves and militarily ineffective against modern European armies.

In 1622, Sultan [Osman II](/Osman_II), angered by military defeats, attempted to disband the Janissaries. Hearing of his plans, they revolted, captured and murdered the young Sultan.

The extravagant lifestyle of the Ottoman elite during the [Tulip Period](/Tulip_Period) fueled public unrest. In 1730, Janissaries, led by [Patrona Halil](/Patrona_Halil), supported a rebellion that led to the abdication of Sultan [Ahmed III](/Ahmed_III) and the death of the Grand Vizier. Though the rebellion was crushed, it marked the end of an era. In 1804, Janissary rulers in Serbia, fearing the Sultan's intentions, massacred prominent Serbian nobles, an event known as the [Slaughter of the Knezes](/Slaughter_of_the_Knezes). This ignited the [Serbian Revolution](/Serbian_Revolution).

In 1807, a Janissary revolt deposed Sultan [Selim III](/Selim_III), who had attempted to create a modern army, the [Nizam-ı Cedid](/Nizam-%C4%B1_Cedid). His supporters failed to regain power before [Mustafa IV](/Mustafa_IV) had him killed, but [Mahmud II](/Mahmud_II) ascended the throne in 1808. Facing Janissary threats, Mahmud II eventually compromised, but spent years discreetly consolidating his power. The Janissaries' abuses, ineffectiveness, resistance to reform, and the sheer cost of maintaining a bloated force made them an intolerable burden.

By 1826, Mahmud II was ready to abolish them. He announced the formation of a new, modern army. As predicted, the Janissaries mutinied, but their barracks were set ablaze by [artillery](/Artillery) fire, resulting in thousands of deaths. The survivors were executed or exiled, their property confiscated. This event, the [Auspicious Incident](/Auspicious_Incident), marked the end of the Janissary Corps. The last were reportedly beheaded in the "Tower of Blood" in [Thessaloniki](/Thessaloniki).

Following their disbandment, Mahmud II established the Mansure Army, later evolving into the modern Ottoman military.

### Janissary Music

The Janissaries' military music, played by the [Mehterân](/Ottoman_military_band), was characterized by powerful percussion and high-pitched winds, featuring instruments like the kös (timpani), davul (bass drum), zurna (shawm), and various trumpets, bells, and cymbals. This distinctive sound influenced European composers such as [Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart](/Wolfgang_Amadeus_Mozart) and [Ludwig van Beethoven](/Ludwig_van_Beethoven), who incorporated "Turkish style" elements into their works.

Sultan Mahmud II disbanded the mehter band in 1826, replacing it with a European-style military band. Today, the tradition of Mehter music is preserved as a cultural heritage, with the band reorganized in 1952 and performing on national holidays and historical occasions.

### Popular Culture

The Janissaries have left their mark on popular culture. In [Bulgaria](/Bulgaria) and [Ukraine](/Ukraine), the word "Janissar" became synonymous with "renegade." They feature in novels such as Jason Goodwin's *The Janissary Tree* and *The Enchantress of Florence* by [Salman Rushdie](/Salman_Rushdie). Jerry Pournelle's novel *Janissaries* also explores their world. Television series like *Muhteşem Yüzyıl* (The Magnificent Century) and *Rise of Empires: Ottoman* have depicted them as part of the Sultan's guard. They are also a unique unit in various video game franchises, including *Civilization*, *Age of Empires*, and *Rise of Nations*. In *Assassin's Creed: Revelations*, Janissaries play a significant role during the reign of Sultan [Bayezid II](/Bayezid_II). The song "Winged Hussars" by [Sabaton](/Sabaton) mentions them in the context of the [Battle of Vienna](/Battle_of_Vienna).

